Text: For me, a theme that emerges throughout the final presentation day was "know thine users".
I mean it seems that all the groups that managed to have a more-or-less finished product had some solid customer research or review behind them.
Or, in the case of Cooks' Brothers, a client who knows exactly what they want and on which platforms the work should be carried out.
Granted, everyone experienced technical difficulties on different degrees, but having a clear road map from the beginning not only helps with productivity, but also motivation and teamwork as well.
I feel like as a team we haven't been able to fully unlock our potentials due to us not being able to finalize our requirements and understand our users better.
This point is elaborated further in my final report.
One thing that I did not have the chance to talk about in the report (due to word limit) is the issue of picking a client.
I should say from the get go that I don't mean to paint Rodney and OB3 in a negative light.
I think our experience of uncertainties and frustration, coupled with the time pressure, technical challenges, and the NDA issue, actually matches up really well to reality.
I also learnt tons of stuff along the way as well, so it's not like our efforts have been wasted for nothing.

But I also think that there are different kinds of realities and at this early stage in our study/career, we may have benefited more had we been exposed to a more, for lack of better word, professional client.
That is to say, since Rodney and Ob3 belongs to the start-up camp, I realized how hard it is for them to juggle many things with little time and resources to spare.

While this testifies to their passion and dedication, an unfortunate consequence is that they can't be experts of everything and in our case we were many times left wondering whether Rodney could be more realistic and to the point.

Adding the fact that Ob3's clearly understaffed and lacks adequate role specialization in their company's structure, I felt like OB3 should be offered at a later stage in SHIFT when we've had some solid practical knowledge, and therefore when the lack of clear requirements and expert mentors would have benefited us more.

At the end of the day, I clearly understand that other factors affect what projects are available, and given Covid and where the economy is heading, I feel very lucky and grateful to have been able to participate a project.

The last paragraph is more like a reminder to myself that I should also take into consideration the maturity and scale of an organisation in relation to my current level of expertise when picking my next project.
In short, a question that I should ask myself is whether an opportunity can teach you the skills you really need at your current level of knowledge and experience.
